properties.name: Community Information
properties.location: Pioneer Bay, St Helier, The Gurdies, Grantville, Jam Jerrup, Lang Lang, Woodleigh
properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for Grantville, Jam Jerrup, Lang Lang, Pioneer Bay, St Helier, The Gurdies, Woodleigh. 

  • There is a bushfire at The Gurdies that is not yet under control.
  • The mild weather conditions over the past few days have resulted in a reduction in fire activity.
  • Ground crews are currently working around the fire edge to extinguish hot spots.
  • There is currently no threat to communities, but you should stay informed and plan for what you will do if the situation changes. 
ROADS:
  • The Bass Highway dual carriageway is now open in both directions and previous speed restrictions have been lifted
  • Gurdies-St Heliers Road is now open. A 40km/h speed limit applies.
  • This Community Information replaces the Community Information issued at 4PM on December 23, 2024.
FORECAST CONDITIONS - CHRISTMAS DAY & BOXING DAY
  • Although there is no immediate threat to the community you should review and update your fire plan now as the situation may change over the next couple of days.
  • Significantly warmer weather with strong and gusty north to north westerly winds are forecast for Boxing Day (26, December).  
  • Due to the increased fire risk a total fire ban has been issued for all of Victoria from midnight on 25 December to midnight on 26 December 2024.

This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by Wednesday, December 25 at 5.00PM or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cathcart, Denicull Creek, Lake Bolac, Langi Logan, Maroona, Mininera, Norval, Rocky Point, Rossbridge, Tatyoon, Tatyoon North, Westmere.

  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap Rd that is not yet under control.
  • High temperatures and strong winds are expected today that may cause increased fire activity. 
  • The Glenelg Highway between Dunkeld and Wickcliffe is NOW CLOSED due to thick smoke. 
  • This Advice replaces the Advice message issued at 6.05am 26 December 2024.
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and plan for what you will do if the situation changes. 
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
  • Find information on protecting yourself and your family: www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare/before-and-during-a-fire
Impacts in your area: 
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
  • You may also see more activity in the air with considerable aerial suppression operations supporting fire fighters on the ground who continue to consolidate control lines.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.transport.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
  • The Glenelg Highway is now closed between Dunkeld and Wickcliffe
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 26/12/2024 09:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

properties.webBody:
This Watch and Act message is being issued for Jallukar, Londonderry, Mafeking, Moyston, Rhymney, Watgania, Willaura North.

  • This Watch and Act replaces the Watch and Act issued at 1.13am Thursday 26/12/2024. 
  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap Road that is not yet under control. 
  • There is a active fire in area, stronger winds will increase fire activity and smoke.  
Don't wait, leaving now is the safest option - conditions may change and get worse very quickly. Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 

What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • Protect yourself and your family. 
  • If you are away from home, do not return.
  • Enact your fire survival plan.
If the situation changes or you feel unsafe you should leave:
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Many people have died trying to leave at the last minute during fires. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning areas to the east
Relief Centres: 
Ararat - Alexandra Oval Community Centre 1 Waratah Ave, Ararat. 
  • Register your attendance at Ararat relief centre via this link.
  • Companion animals are welcome, but must remain on a lead at all times.  Please ensure you bring any necessary items for your animals such as food, water bowl and bedding. 
Stawell - Grampians Community Health (known as "The Shacc"), 22 Patrick Street Stawell. This centre is currently unstaffed until 6.00am Thursday 26 December. People requiring immediate assistance can utilise the contacts listed on the door, more information is available from Northern Grampians Shire Website 
  • Register your attendance at Stawell relief centre via this link
  • Pets are welcome, please ensure they are on a lead at all times.

Anyone can register with Red Cross via the Register.Find.Reunite so your family and friends can find you.

Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. You must monitor conditions and be ready to act.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
  • Bushfires can spread quickly and are extremely dangerous.
  • Bushfires can start spot fires and embers can travel large distances ahead of the main fire
  • The Grampians National Park remains closed. For more information visit the Parks Victoria website.
Relief Centres
Ararat - Alexandra Oval Community Centre 1 Waratah Ave, Ararat. 
  • Register your attendance at Ararat via this link.
  • Companion animals are welcome, but must remain on a lead at all times.  Please ensure you bring any necessary items for your animals such as food, water bowl and bedding.  
Stawell - Grampians Community Health (known as "The Shacc")22 Patrick Street Stawell. 
  • Pets are welcome, please ensure they are on a lead at all times. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 27/12/2024 10:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.location: the area south of Pomonal near Redman Road and Long Gully Road
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for the area south of Pomonal near Redman Rd and Long Gully Rd. 
  • This Emergency Warning replaces the Emergency Warning issued at 6:28pm Wednesday 25/12/2024. The warning area has been changed.  
  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap Road that is not yet under control. 
  • The bushfire is travelling from Grampians National Park in a southerly direction towards Redman Road and Long Gully Road.  
  • Private property adjoining the National Park could be impacted in the next 2-4 hours, south of the Pomonal 2024 fire area.
Leaving immediately is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.
What you should do: 

Travel to: 
  • The home of family or friends that is away from the warning area.
  • You should leave using Ararat Halls Gap Road and head towards Ararat or Stawell. 
  • When you leave remember to take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
Relief Centres

Ararat - Alexandra Oval Community Centre 1 Waratah Ave, Ararat. 
  • Register your attendance at Ararat via this link
  • Companion animals are welcome, but must remain on a lead at all times.  Please ensure you bring any necessary items for your animals such as food, water bowl and bedding.  

Stawell - Grampians Community Health (known as "The Shacc")22 Patrick Street Stawell is unstaffed until 6.00am Thursday 26 December. 
  • Register your attendance at Stawell via this link
  • People requiring immediate assistance can utilise the contacts listed on the door. Pets are welcome, please ensure they are on a lead at all times. 

Anyone can register with Red Cross via the Register.Find.Reunite so your family and friends can find you.

In the car: 
  • If you are travelling, do not enter the area. Make a u-turn and travel to safety.
  • Slow down and turn on your headlights. Smoke will make it difficult to see.

If you are unable to leave you should shelter indoors:
  • Close all exterior doors, windows and vents. Turn off cooling systems.
  • You must take shelter before the fire arrives. The extreme heat is likely to kill you well before the flames reach you.
  • Shelter in a room that has two exits, such as a door or window including one directly to the outside. It is important to be able to see outside so you know what is happening with the fire. 
  • If your home catches on fire and the conditions inside become unbearable, you need to get out and go to an area that has already been burnt. 

If you cannot get indoors, other last resort options include:
  • Shelter in the middle of a large open area like a ploughed paddock, football oval or sporting reserve.
  • Get into a large body of water like a dam, lake, river, the ocean or inground pool.
  • Try to protect yourself from the fire's heat.

If you are caught in fire in your car:
  • Park behind a solid structure to block the fire's heat or pull over to cleared area.
  • Try to position the car towards the approaching fire.
  • Turn on your hazard lights and headlights.
  • Close all windows.
  • Turn off the air-conditioning and shut all the air vents.
  • Turn your car engine off.
  • Get down as low as possible below window level and cover up with a pure woollen blanket.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.transport.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
  • Trees can fall across roads and cause dangerous driving conditions. Please avoid travelling today and tomorrow.
  • Bushfires can start spot fires and embers can travel large distances ahead of the main fire.
  • The Grampians National Park remains closed. For more information visit the Parks Victoria website.

This messages was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 27/12/2024 06:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Watch and Act message is being issued for Jimmy Creek, Karabeal, Mirranatwa, Strathmore, Victoria Valley, Grampians, Victoria Point.

This Watch and Action replaces the message issued at 10:54pm Wednesday 25/12/2024.
  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap road that is not yet under control.  
  • There may be increased fire activity in the Mirranatwa and Brady Swamp areas of the Grampians National Park. 
The situation can change at any time. You must monitor conditions and be ready to act.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing. 
  • You will see an increase in aerial fire suppression activity throughout today
  • Enact your fire survival plan now. If your plan is to leave, leave early. 
  • If you have time, check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions. 
  • Protect yourself and your family.
Leave if the situation changes or you feel unsafe. 

Remember to:
  • When you leave take your medications, mobile phone charger and other necessary items you will need.  
  • Take your pets.  Ensure you have a lead, food and water for them.  
  • Many people have tried to leave at the last minute during fires.
  • Travel to the home of family and friends in a safer location south west of the Grampians region. 
Relief Centres
Ararat - Alexandra Oval Community Centre 1 Waratah Ave, Ararat. 
  • Register your attendance at Ararat via this link.
  • Companion animals are welcome, but must remain on a lead at all times.  Please ensure you bring any necessary items for your animals such as food, water bowl and bedding.

  • Register your attendance at Stawell via this link.
  • People requiring immediate assistance can utilise the contacts listed on the door. Pets are welcome, please ensure they are on a lead at all times. 
Anyone can register with Red Cross via the Register.Find.Reunite so your family and friends can find you.
Impacts in your area:
  • Bushfires can spread quickly and are extremely dangerous.
  • Trees can be extremely dangerous during a bushfire or high winds. Do not stand, park or travel in areas of fire affected trees.
  • Bushfires can start spot fires and embers can travel large distances ahead of the main fire.

Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.transport.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.

The Grampians National Park remains CLOSED for more information visit the Parks Victoria website.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 27/12/2024 10:10 am or as the situation changes.

This Watch and Act message is being issued for Willaura, Stavely, Kia Ora. 

  • This Watch and Act replaces the Watch and Act issued at 6:16pm Wednesday 25/12/2024. 
  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap Rd that is not yet under control. 
  •  The bushfire is travelling in a south-easterly direction. The fire is active in the Bornes Hill area and may be visible. 
The situation can change at any time. You must monitor conditions and be ready to act.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing. 
  • Warmer temperatures with increasing northerly winds will see an increase in fire activity and smoke.
  • You will see an increase in aerial fire suppression activity throughout today
  • Enact your fire survival plan now. If your plan is to leave, leave early. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes. 
  • If you have time, check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions. 
  • Protect yourself and your family.
Relief Centres Now Open: 
Ararat - Alexandra Oval Community Centre 1 Waratah Ave, Ararat. 
  • Register your attendance at Ararat via this link
  • Companion animals are welcome, but must remain on a lead at all times.  Please ensure you bring any necessary items for your animals such as food, water bowl and bedding.  

Stawell - Grampians Community Health (known as "The Shacc"), 22 Patrick Street Stawell is unstaffed until 6.00am Thursday 26 December. 
  • Register your attendance at Stawell via this link
  • People requiring immediate assistance can utilise the contacts listed on the door. Pets are welcome, please ensure they are on a lead at all times. 
Anyone can register with Red Cross via the Register.Find.Reunite so your family and friends can find you.

Recordings of Community Meetings are available from the VicEmergency - Grampians Facebook Page.

Leave if the situation changes or you feel unsafe. 
Remember to:
  • When you leave take your medications, mobile phone charger and other necessary items you will need.  
  • Take your pets.  Ensure you have a lead, food and water for them.   
  • Many people have died trying to leave at the last minute during fires. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area south west of the Grampians Region
Impacts in your area:
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.transport.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
  • Trees can fall across roads and cause dangerous driving conditions. 
  • Bushfires can start spot fires and embers can travel large distances ahead of the main fire.

The Grampians National Park remains CLOSED. For more information visit the Parks Victoria website.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 26/12/2024 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires) 
  • ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • For information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Bullengarook.

  • The bushfire at Bullengarook has been contained but is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire started near Coffeys Road and is burning within the Wombat State Forest.
  • Crews will continue working over the coming days to make the fire safe.
  • Extreme fire weather expected on Thursday may increase the risk to life and property south and east of the fire.
  • You should plan to leave early, before conditions become too dangerous.
Stay informed, monitor conditions and plan for what you will do if the situation changes. 
What you should do: 
  • Enact your fire survival plan. If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes. 
  • Leaving early is the safest option.
  • Find information on protecting yourself and your family: http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare/before-and-during-a-fire 
  • Monitor weather conditions and be ready to act. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, seeing smoke and having poor visibility all indicate the situation is changing.
  • Listen to ABC Central Victoria 91.1FM or ABC Radio Melbourne 774 AM. 
  • Take your phone off silent and make sure notifications are turned on. 
  • Have a battery powered radio on hand and spare batteries or use the car radio to stay informed. 
  • Reach out to your neighbours, friends and family to make sure they are aware of the situation. 
  • When leaving, open all internal gates to allow stock and animals to move freely around your property if threatened by fire, however leave external gates closed.
People who intend to stay must:
  • Be physically and mentally prepared to be isolated and come under threat. 
  • Have a comprehensive plan, drinking water supply, equipment and a survival place of last resort. 
  • Have prepared inside and outside their house, including pets, animals, equipment and vehicles. 
  • Remember fire trucks will be concentrating on stopping the fire spread and not necessarily protecting individual properties.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Bushfires can spread quickly and are extremely dangerous.
  • Smoke may be more visible to nearby communities during the warmer and windier parts of the day, typically afternoons.
  • Coffeys Road, Carrolls Lane and Waterloo Flat Road are closed.
  • Numerous tracks within the Wombat State Forest are closed, including Finger Post Road and a number of adjoining tracks.
  • If you are travelling, plan ahead. Check Fire Danger Ratings and check the VicTraffic website or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
Pyschosocial support:
This festive season may be particularly stressful for communities impacted by bushfires. If you or someone you know is feeling overwhelmed, or just need someone to talk to, there are free 24/7 supports available. 
  • Lifeline 13 11 14 
  • Beyond Blue 1300 22 4636 
  • Kids Helpline 1800 55 1800
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 26/12/2024 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Bornes Hill and North Boundary Road area.

  • There is a bushfire at Grampians National Park - Yarram Gap road that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is travelling in a southerly direction towards Wannon River and is spotting into the North Boundary Road area. 
  • It is too late to leave the area safely so you must take shelter now.
  • Firefighters are responding to this area. 
You are in danger and need to act immediately to survive.

The safest option is to take shelter indoors immediately. It is too late to leave.
What you should do:
You should move indoors: 
  • Protect yourself by wearing long sleeves and trousers, made from pure cotton or wool. Wear leather boots.  
  • Bring your pets inside.  
  • Close all exterior doors, windows and vents and turn off cooling systems. 
  • You must take shelter before the fire arrives. The extreme heat is likely to kill you well before the flames reach you. 
  • Shelter in a room that has two exits, such as a door or window including one directly to the outside. It is important to be able to see outside so you know what is happening with the fire.

If your home catches on fire: 
  • Move away from the rooms that are on fire, closing doors behind you.
  • As soon as the bushfire has passed the house, or conditions inside become unbearable, you need to get out and go to an area that has already been burnt. Staying inside a burning building will almost certainly end in death. 
  • It may still be too hot to remain outside, so you will need to seek shelter in another structure or last resort option.

If you cannot get indoors, last resort options include:
  • Shelter in the middle of a large open area like a ploughed paddock, football oval or sporting reserve.
  • Get into a large body of water like a dam, lake, river, the ocean or inground pool.
  • Try to protect yourself from the fire's heat.

If you are travelling: 
  • If you are travelling, do not enter the warning area. Make a u-turn and travel to safety. 
  • If you are currently driving slow down and turn on your headlights. Smoke will make it difficult to see.

If you are caught in fire in your car: 
  • Park off the road behind a solid structure to block the fire's heat or pull over to cleared area.
  • Try to position the car towards the approaching fire.
  • Turn on your hazard lights and headlights.
  • Close all windows. 
  • Turn off the air-conditioning and shut all the air vents. 
  • Turn your car engine off. 
  • Get down as low as possible below window level and cover up with a pure woollen blanket.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Embers are starting small fires ahead of the main fire.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 26/12/2024 10:50 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
